<p>Once eaten, never forgotten is the texture of a well made quenelle. Mixtu-</p>
<p>res of minced and pounded meat which may be veal, chicken, game, fish, </p>
<p>shellfish together with butter, seasonings, eggs and sometimes cream.</p>
<p>There are a number of methods of shaping the quenelle – by hand, with a </p>
<p>piping bag, with a spoon or in molds. They are cooked uncovered in sim-</p>
<p>mering water or stock, but care should be taken to ensure that the liquid </p>
<p>does not boil rapidly or the quenelles Will break.</p>
<p>À la cuiller 
(molded by spoon)</p>
<p>Shaped by soup, dessert or coffee 
spoon. Have ready a pan of boiling 
water and 2 spoons. 
Dip one spoon in the boiling water 
while filling the other generously 
with the quenelle mixture. At this 
point a knife can be used to smooth 
the quenelle in
 a dome shape.
Then take the other spoon out of the 
hot water and loosen the quenelle 
without spoiling its shape. Place the 
quenelle in the buttered pan and 
continue with the resto f the quenel-
les, always dipping one spoon in hot 
water. Leave room for
 the quenelles to expand.</p>
